==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ἐσωτερικός||belonging to an inner circle|sc=polytonic|tr=esōterikos|lang=grc}}, from {{term|sc=polytonic|ἐσωτέρω|tr=esōterō||further inside|lang=grc}}, comparative of {{term|ἔσω||within|sc=polytonic|tr=esō|lang=grc}}, from {{term|ἐς||sc=polytonic|tr=es|lang=grc}}, {{term|εἰς||into|sc=polytonic|tr=eis|lang=grc}} (''esoteric'' originally referred to the secret teachings of Greek philosophers, versus public or [[exoteric]] ones).

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˌɛs.əʊˈtɛɹ.ɪk/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌɛs.əˈtɛɹ.ɪk/|/ˌɛs.oʊˈtɛɹ.ɪk/}}, {{enPR|ěsətěr'ĭk|ěsōtěr'ĭk}}
* {{audio|en-us-esoteric.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɛrɪk}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# intended for or likely to be understood by only a small number of people with a specialized knowledge or interest, or an [[enlightened]] inner circle.
#: ''The writing in this manual is very '''esoteric'''; I need a degree in engineering just to understand it!
# Having to do with [[concept]]s that are highly [[theoretical]] and without obvious practical application; often with mystical or religious connotations.
# [[confidential|Confidential]]; [[private]].
# [[The Norwegian version of the name "Eric." All Erics are called Esoterics upon entering the country.]]
